entry.title: [media session] Don't request audio focus quite so much
entry.content:
MediaSessionImpl::AddPlayer is called very often, such as when any

metadata changes. Previously, it would request audio focus at this

point if the session is eligible.



Unfortunately, if the player is paused, but is not at the end of

the stream, then this has the effect of requesting the audio focus

at more or less random times. On android, where audio focus is

more strongly enforced, this can take the audio focus from other

chrome tabs / non-chrome applications and cause them to stop

producing audio.



This CL changes this behavior so that a paused stream that might

start playing later does not request the audio focus if it doesn't

already have it. Instead, it sets its state to `SUSPENDED`, which

is the state that happens on pause (== no audio focus, but is

controllable). This handles the case where it's paused and some

random update causes an `AddPlayer()`, and also the case where it

has reached EOS (== `INACTIVE` -- not controllable, not really an

interesting stream) but has just un-entered EOS and should become

controllable again.



When playback starts, it will re-request audio focus.



Bug: b/40944611

entry.content:

was introduced into the AppMenuModel so that after a single install,

entry.title: Introduce base::cstring_view
entry.content:
We currently have vocabulary types to receive a string parameter:

- std::string for owning + NUL-terminated

- std::string_view for non-owning and non-NUL-terminated

- const char* for non-owning and NUL-terminated



However the use of const char* will require unsafe pointer arithmetic

which is incompatible with -Wunsafe-buffer-usage (every use of the

pointer will cause compilation errors) so we need an alternative way

to express NUL-terminated string views that include bounds safety.

This type will allow conversion from pointer, or pointer+len, to a

bounds-safe view type that maintains its NUL terminator.



Throwing away the NUL byte is not a good option, as it forces a copy

into a std::string every time you want the NUL again. We should have

a non-owning view type that encodes in the type system that there is

a NUL terminator, and which provides a .c_str() method to get the

NUL-terminated pointer for C apis like string has.



So far the type has:

- default ctor

- ctor from ptr+len [unsafe buffer usage]

- ctor from string literal

- c_str

- data/size

- size_bytes (like span)

- begin/end/cbegin/cend

- operator[]

- operator==

- operator<=>



Eventually it will have all of string_view API, plus:

- have .c_str() representing that it returns a NUL-terminated char

pointer suitable for passing to C APIs (done).

- be constructible from string literal (done).

- have a template parameter to retain compile-time size when possible,

like span (done).

- avoid holding a size field when it's known at compile time, like

span (done).



In order to use them, introduce the following macros in base:

- LIFETIME_BOUND

- PURE_FUNCTION

As proposed in the cxx@ thread:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/lVQOJTng1RU/m/91r04iLAAwAJ



As well as the __attribute__((enable_if())) extension via the macro

in order to catch bugs at compile time and ensure cstring_view is

only constructed from string literals (and not non-NUL-terminated

char arrays):

- ENABLE_IF_ATTR

entry.title: [PIX] Do not return null pointer when factory uses old interface
entry.content:
Before this patch, if a subclass of FacilitatedPaymentsApiClient.Factory

did not implement the two-parameter factoryCreate(renderFrameHost,

delegate) method used by the JNI bridge, then the default implementation

of the factory would return null, causing the JNI bridge to throw a

NullPointerException when attempting to invoke methods in the API

client. The factory implementation cannot be updated at the same time as

the factory interface, because the interface is in Chromium, while the

factory is in Clank.



This patch changes the default implementation of the two-parameter

factoryCreate(renderFrameHost, delegate) method from returning null to

invoking the single-parameter method factoryCreate(delegate). The

FacilitatedPaymentsApiClient.create() method now also asserts that the

factory is returning a non-null object instance.



After this patch, the JNI bridge does not throw a NullPointerException.

entry.title: message_pump_android: Do not instrument callbacks
entry.content:
When orderfile instrumentation is enabled, every function gets

instrumented with an additional call to the hook

__cyg_profile_func_enter_bare() somewhere in the prologue. We define

this hook to (among other things) pull __builtin_return_address(0) and

check that it is within the address range of .text.



We observed repeatedly on the orderfile bot that on instrumented builds

the __builtin_return_address(0) returns incorrect results for

instrumented functions DelayedLooperCallback() and

NonDelayedLooperCallback(). These are somewhat special calls, as they

are made from /system/lib64/libutils.so using an indirect call.



My main hypothesis is that the ABI may not be fully respected with these

cross-library calls (and when aggressive PGO optimizations are applied).

The issue needs a more thorough investigation.



For now, apply a speculative pseudofix: exclude these functions from

instrumentation. If it does not fix the issue on the orderfile bot, the

hypothesis above would be rejected.

entry.content:
Explainer:

https://github.com/fserb/canvas2D/blob/master/spec/webgpu.md



Previously, endWebGPUAccess was an entirely empty stub which did

nothing.



It is still largely unimplemented, but endWebGPUAccess now

entry.content:
The spec says that the "form" role only makes it a "landmark" if there

is an accessible name.



ARIA 1.3 says that the form role is a sub-role of landmark:

https://w3c.github.io/aria/, so if there is no accessible role then

the "form" role is inappropriate.

it should be "section"? That's what Chromium currently does), I

entry.title: Address slowness of WPT
entry.content:
prefer-targeted-element-main-frame.html is timing out on quite a few

builders[1]. On "Win10 Tests x64" for example, even when it passes, it

often takes ~5.5 seconds which is super close to the timeout limit of 6

seconds. This patch attempts to make the test less slow.



Prior to this patch, the test opened 9 windows, running one test per

window. With this patch, the test will run all 9 tests in the same

window by making use of the location.hash API.

entry.title: Make URLRequest::delegate_ no longer dangle.
entry.content:
In particular, make WebSocketStreamRequestImpl, which owns both a

URLRequest and a URLRequest::Delegate, delete its URLRequest before

the Delegate the URLRequest has a pointer to in the case of

successfully establishing a WebSocket connection.



Also make some ThroughputAnalyzerTest destroy a vector of URLRequests

after a vector of their URLRequest::Delegates.



None of these could actually result in a UAF in production code

(or even test code), they just triggered the dangling pointer

detector, preventing it from being enabled for URLRequest::delegate_.
